If we can transform it into our built environment, then the way we build things will have a lot of potential.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences -- basically, the DNA of how our buildings work.
Then we need the programmable part to accept the sequence and use it for folding or remodeling.
We need some energy to activate, so that these parts of us can be folded up according to the procedure.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to make sure that what we build successfully is what we want.
